WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.080
So I'm going to present on updates on Xanubrutinib and Senrodoclax as a treatment approach in CLL, and I'm going to try to contextualize this alongside other BTK-BCL2 doublet data.

00:00:12.680 --> 00:00:39.800
These are my disclosures, and so I'm not going to belabor this slide again because we've presented this now a few times, but this just to highlight again that the CLL17 data demonstrated that fixed-duration therapies with VO or IV achieve similar PFS, and that progression really means different things between these arms, treatment failure with abrutinib versus potential continued clinical benefit for the fixed-duration therapies.

00:00:40.100 --> 00:00:53.340
If you ask patients, as has been done in the VOICE survey study, not shown here, the vast majority of patients prefer all oral therapies, and a majority of patients prefer time-limited therapies.

00:00:53.520 --> 00:00:58.000
And so there would clearly be an interest in a BTK-BCL2 doublet.

00:00:58.560 --> 00:01:02.960
However, there's limited enthusiasm for abrutinib-based therapies, at least in the United States.

00:01:04.100 --> 00:01:09.580
So how do the second-generation inhibitors fare in combination with venetoclax?

00:01:09.680 --> 00:01:09.960
I'm going to highlight.

00:01:10.100 --> 00:01:15.620
I'm going to highlight the acalabrutinib venetoclax data from the Phase III Amplify trial shown here.

00:01:15.620 --> 00:01:34.240
In the Amplify study, patients with treatment-naive CLL in the absence of a P53 deletion or mutation were randomized to AV, AVO, or chemoimmunotherapy, demonstrating superior progression-free survival with AV over chemoimmunotherapy, leading to its recent FDA approval.

00:01:34.440 --> 00:01:36.800
But there's some very clear questions that remain.

00:01:36.800 --> 00:01:39.720
So first, can we extrapolate the CLL17 data?

00:01:40.100 --> 00:01:40.980
To A plus V?

00:01:41.100 --> 00:01:42.080
I'm not sure we can.

00:01:42.180 --> 00:01:51.960
I think we need longer follow-up before we feel comfortable that we're seeing similar results with AV doublet.

00:01:52.460 --> 00:02:06.560
However, this is clearly an excellent option for patients with treatment-naive CLL who require therapy, want fixed-duration therapy, are good candidates for a covalent BTK inhibitor, and strongly prefer not to receive an infusional therapy.

00:02:06.860 --> 00:02:10.080
Also, how do P53-abarant CLL patients?

00:02:10.100 --> 00:02:11.360
I think it's fair with this treatment.

00:02:11.960 --> 00:02:16.560
I also think that an important feature of this regimen is that it still includes venetoclax.

00:02:16.560 --> 00:02:24.100
And venetoclax uptake remains limited, in particular in the community setting, related to the ramp-up and STAT lab requirement.

00:02:24.740 --> 00:02:28.180
And so there remains a need to improve feasibility.

00:02:29.480 --> 00:02:39.020
So we really do need to address these feasibility issues and also to improve upon the safety and tolerability of BCL2 inhibitors.

00:02:39.260 --> 00:02:39.920
And

00:02:40.100 --> 00:02:45.580
potentially to improve upon the efficacy of BCL2 inhibitor-based therapies in CLL.

00:02:46.320 --> 00:02:47.940
So what is the optimal ramp-up?

00:02:48.420 --> 00:03:01.040
I would argue that probably the best ramp-up with a BCL2-based therapy is one in which we can either reduce or even potentially obviate the need for TLS laboratory monitoring, again, to make this more feasible in the community setting.

00:03:01.580 --> 00:03:08.860
This is something that's being evaluated in the Venetian trial, which is evaluating novel venetoclax ramp-up strategies with VO or AV strategies.

