tumor lysis syndrome, GI treatment emergent adverse events, and important toxicity for

00:06:51.820 --> 00:06:57.100
patients on BCL-2 inhibitors are relatively uncommon and predominantly grade 1 with this

00:06:57.100 --> 00:07:02.380
combination. Grade 3 or worse, the most common grade 3 or worse treatment emergent adverse event

00:07:02.380 --> 00:07:07.660
was neutropenia, but this did not appear to result in increased grade 3 or worse infections,

00:07:08.220 --> 00:07:14.520
and no fatal treatment emergent adverse events, complicated COVID-19 cases, or deaths occurred

00:07:14.520 --> 00:07:20.560
on study. This combination demonstrated substantial efficacy in treatment-naive CLL

00:07:20.560 --> 00:07:28.220
with high rates of UMRD-4, particularly at the 320-milligram dose, supporting the 320-milligram

00:07:28.220 --> 00:07:34.500
dose selection for further study in the phase 3 trials. In the 320-milligram dose cohort, again,

00:07:34.640 --> 00:07:42.280
81% were UMRD-4 at week 24, 91% at UMRD-4, which is highly encouraging, and responses appear quite

00:07:42.280 --> 00:07:42.640
durable.

00:07:43.000 --> 00:07:48.180
Now, of course, the million-dollar question is whether this is better than VO or AV,

00:07:48.820 --> 00:07:53.200
and this is being addressed in two prospective randomized phase 3 trials,

00:07:53.660 --> 00:08:02.420
including the CELESTIAL study comparing ZS with VO and the upcoming study of ZS compared with AV,

00:08:02.840 --> 00:08:06.180
again, both in treatment-naive CLL of all risk groups.

00:08:06.960 --> 00:08:10.580
Finally, the key question is about feasibility, right? So,

00:08:11.480 --> 00:08:18.480
what will the final Synrhodoclax ramp-up strategy be? Will this address the feasibility issues that

00:08:18.480 --> 00:08:22.640
have really limited Venetoclax uptake in the community to date? Thank you for your attention.
